    mechanism:
      "**γ-glutamyl-cysteinyl-glycine** — a tripeptide synthesized in nearly every cell of the body from the constituent amino acids glutamate, cysteine, and glycine via the sequential action of glutamate-cysteine ligase (the rate-limiting enzyme) and glutathione synthetase. Glutathione is the most abundant intracellular thiol-containing molecule and the master antioxidant of cellular redox biology. **Mechanism — direct antioxidant via reactive thiol (the central effect)**: glutathione's central pharmacological feature is the reactive sulfhydryl (-SH) group on its cysteine residue, which donates an electron to neutralize reactive oxygen species (ROS), reactive nitrogen species (RNS), and other oxidative threats. The reaction produces glutathione disulfide (GSSG) — two oxidized glutathione molecules linked by a disulfide bond — which is then reduced back to GSH by glutathione reductase using NADPH as the electron donor. The GSH/GSSG ratio is the principal cellular redox status indicator; healthy cells maintain a GSH/GSSG ratio of approximately 100:1, with the ratio declining toward 1:1 under oxidative stress, aging, and chronic disease states. **Mechanism — cofactor for glutathione peroxidase (the enzymatic antioxidant role)**: glutathione is the obligate cofactor for the glutathione peroxidase enzyme family — selenium-dependent enzymes that reduce hydrogen peroxide and lipid peroxides to water and the corresponding alcohols. The glutathione peroxidase reaction is one of the principal enzymatic antioxidant defenses in human cells and is the basis for selenium's antioxidant function (selenium is the active site cofactor for glutathione peroxidase). **Mechanism — substrate for glutathione S-transferase (the Phase II detoxification role)**: glutathione is the substrate for the glutathione S-transferase enzyme family — a major Phase II detoxification system that conjugates glutathione to electrophilic xenobiotics (drugs, environmental toxins, carcinogens, lipid peroxidation products) to form water-soluble glutathione conjugates that can be excreted via bile or urine. The GST detoxification pathway is the principal route for clearing acetaminophen overdose metabolites (NAPQI), polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, alkylating agents, and many other electrophilic toxins. **Mechanism — cysteine reservoir and methylation cycle intersection**: glutathione synthesis requires cysteine, which is the rate-limiting precursor amino acid. Cysteine is derived from dietary methionine via the transsulfuration pathway (methionine → homocysteine → cystathionine → cysteine → glutathione), placing glutathione synthesis at the downstream end of the methylation cycle. Adequate methylation cycle function (B12, folate, B6, betaine, choline) supports cysteine availability and therefore glutathione synthesis. The intersection is part of why methylation support and glutathione support are common companion interventions in integrative medicine practice. **Mechanism — protein and DNA modifications via S-glutathionylation**: glutathione can covalently modify protein cysteine residues (S-glutathionylation), modulating protein function in redox-sensitive signaling networks. The S-glutathionylation modification is increasingly recognized as a regulatory post-translational modification with effects on enzyme activity, protein-protein interactions, and signaling cascades. **Mechanism — multi-route bioavailability profile**: glutathione bioavailability varies dramatically by route. **IV** delivers full pharmacological dose directly to circulation; the gold standard for clinical use. **SubQ / IM** provides sustained systemic exposure with simpler administration. **Oral** glutathione has historically poor bioavailability due to GI peptidase degradation and limited intestinal absorption; modern liposomal oral glutathione formulations substantially improve bioavailability vs unprotected oral glutathione. **Inhaled / nebulized** delivers glutathione to airway epithelium for pulmonary indications. **Topical** delivers glutathione to skin for cosmetic skin-lightening applications. **N-acetylcysteine (NAC) oral** is an alternative oral precursor strategy — NAC supplies cysteine for endogenous glutathione synthesis with substantially better oral bioavailability than glutathione itself. **Pharmaceutical status**: glutathione is NOT FDA-approved as a pharmaceutical drug for any indication; available as compounded preparation via compounding pharmacies. NAC has FDA approval as Acetadote (IV for acetaminophen overdose) and as Mucomyst (inhaled mucolytic). **Pharmacokinetics**: plasma half-life ~minutes when administered as glutathione directly; cellular half-life of glutathione pool is hours to days depending on tissue and oxidative load. SubQ/IM dosing typically several times weekly; IV dosing typically weekly to daily depending on clinical context.",
