    mechanism:
      "**Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide** — a dinucleotide composed of two nucleotides joined by a pyrophosphate bridge: one with an adenine base and one with nicotinamide (the amide form of niacin / vitamin B3). NAD+ exists in two forms in cells: NAD+ (oxidized, electron acceptor) and NADH (reduced, electron donor). The NAD+/NADH redox pair participates in approximately 500 enzymatic reactions across central metabolism — making NAD+ one of the most broadly utilized coenzymes in human biology. **Mechanism — central electron carrier in cellular metabolism (the foundational role)**: NAD+ accepts electrons from substrates in catabolic reactions (glycolysis, fatty acid oxidation, citric acid cycle, ethanol metabolism), becoming reduced to NADH. NADH then donates electrons to the mitochondrial electron transport chain at Complex I, driving ATP synthesis via oxidative phosphorylation. The NAD+/NADH cycling is the principal electron transfer mechanism for cellular energy production; without sufficient NAD+, cellular energy metabolism stalls. **Mechanism — substrate for sirtuins (the longevity connection)**: sirtuins (SIRT1-7 in humans) are NAD+-dependent deacetylases that remove acetyl groups from histone and non-histone proteins, modulating gene expression, protein function, and cellular stress responses. Sirtuins consume NAD+ stoichiometrically — each deacetylation reaction cleaves NAD+ to nicotinamide + ADP-ribose intermediates. Sirtuin activity is implicated in: caloric restriction-mediated lifespan extension (across model organisms from yeast to mammals), mitochondrial biogenesis (SIRT1, SIRT3), DNA damage response (SIRT6), circadian rhythm regulation, and metabolic homeostasis. The sirtuin-NAD+ axis is the principal mechanistic substrate for NAD+ supplementation as a longevity intervention and was popularized in mainstream science communication via David Sinclair's research at Harvard and his book 'Lifespan' (2019). **Mechanism — substrate for PARPs (the DNA repair connection)**: poly(ADP-ribose) polymerases (PARP1, PARP2, others) are NAD+-dependent enzymes that ribosylate proteins as part of DNA damage response. PARP activation in response to DNA damage consumes NAD+ rapidly — severe DNA damage can deplete cellular NAD+ pools to the point of cellular dysfunction. The PARP-NAD+ relationship is part of why oxidative stress and DNA damage states are associated with NAD+ depletion. **Mechanism — substrate for CD38 (the age-related decline driver)**: CD38 is a NAD+-consuming ectoenzyme expressed on immune cells and other tissues. CD38 expression and activity increase with age — driving accelerated NAD+ consumption that contributes substantially to the age-related decline in NAD+ levels (~50% reduction by middle age in many tissues). CD38-mediated NAD+ depletion is a proposed mechanistic component of aging-associated cellular dysfunction; CD38 inhibitors (apigenin, quercetin, luteolinidin, others) are an active research area for NAD+ preservation strategies. **Mechanism — multi-route bioavailability and the precursor strategy**: NAD+ has very short plasma half-life (~minutes) and limited cellular uptake of intact NAD+; the cellular NAD+ pool is largely synthesized de novo from precursors entering specific metabolic pathways. The NAD+ precursor landscape includes: **NMN (nicotinamide mononucleotide)** — direct NAD+ precursor converted via NMNAT enzymes; oral bioavailability in humans debated; intracellular conversion to NAD+ established. **NR (nicotinamide riboside)** — precursor converted via NRK enzymes; commercialized as Niagen (ChromaDex); oral bioavailability well-established; substantial clinical evidence base. **NA (nicotinic acid / niacin)** — classical NAD+ precursor; flushing is dose-limiting at higher doses; cardiovascular indications historically (LDL/HDL effects). **NAM (nicotinamide)** — non-flushing NAD+ precursor; high-dose NAM may inhibit sirtuins (theoretical concern relevant for longevity-focused use). **Tryptophan** — de novo NAD+ synthesis precursor via the kynurenine pathway; minor contribution at typical dietary intake. The precursor strategy is the principal practical NAD+ support approach for daily / oral use; direct IV/SubQ NAD+ is reserved for clinical infusion and research peptide community injectable contexts. **Pharmaceutical status**: NAD+ is NOT FDA-approved as a pharmaceutical drug for any indication; available as compounded preparation. NAD+ precursors (NMN, NR, NA, NAM) are sold as dietary supplements. **Pharmacokinetics**: plasma NAD+ half-life ~minutes; cellular pool turnover hours to days depending on tissue and metabolic load.",
