    mechanism:
      "**28-amino-acid neuropeptide** belonging to the secretin / glucagon peptide family (along with PACAP, GLP-1, GIP, growth hormone-releasing hormone, and others). Originally isolated from porcine intestinal extracts in 1970, VIP is a foundational neuropeptide with widespread distribution in the central nervous system, peripheral autonomic nervous system, and gastrointestinal tract. Despite the name reflecting its discovery in intestinal extracts, VIP's roles span vasodilation, smooth muscle relaxation, neurotransmission, immunomodulation, and circadian rhythm regulation. **Mechanism — VPAC1, VPAC2, and PAC1 receptor agonism (the central effects)**: VIP binds and activates three G-protein-coupled receptors with overlapping but tissue-distinct expression patterns: **VPAC1** (broad expression including immune cells, smooth muscle, and CNS), **VPAC2** (CNS, immune cells, smooth muscle), and **PAC1** (the principal PACAP receptor, also activated by VIP at lower potency). All three receptors couple primarily to Gαs → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP elevation as the principal downstream signaling cascade; secondary signaling via Gαq, MAPK, and PI3K pathways occurs in tissue-specific contexts. The receptor multiplicity supports VIP's pleiotropic effects across so many physiological systems. **Mechanism — vasodilation and smooth muscle relaxation (the foundational systemic effects)**: VIP is one of the most potent endogenous vasodilators identified. cAMP elevation in vascular smooth muscle drives smooth muscle relaxation and vasodilation. The same cAMP-mediated relaxation occurs in GI smooth muscle (driving GI motility effects, including the watery diarrhea associated with VIPomas — VIP-secreting tumors), bronchial smooth muscle (driving bronchodilation, the basis for aviptadil's investigation in pulmonary diseases), and other smooth muscle beds. The vasodilation is the principal mechanism behind VIP's hypotension side effect at higher systemic doses. **Mechanism — anti-inflammatory and immunomodulatory effects (the CIRS protocol substrate)**: VIP receptors are expressed on T-cells, macrophages, dendritic cells, and other immune cells. cAMP elevation in immune cells produces broadly anti-inflammatory effects: shifting T-helper cell responses from Th1/Th17 toward Th2/Treg, inhibiting pro-inflammatory cytokine production (TNF-α, IL-6, IL-1β), promoting regulatory T-cell function, and dampening macrophage / dendritic cell pro-inflammatory activation. The anti-inflammatory profile is the principal mechanistic substrate for VIP's use in chronic inflammatory states, particularly in the **Shoemaker CIRS (Chronic Inflammatory Response Syndrome) protocol** developed by Ritchie Shoemaker MD for biotoxin illness recovery. **Mechanism — circadian rhythm and CNS effects**: VIP is a key neurotransmitter in the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN), the central circadian pacemaker. VIP signaling synchronizes SCN neuron firing patterns and supports circadian rhythm maintenance. Disrupted VIP signaling in CIRS and other chronic illness states is part of the mechanistic framework for sleep and circadian rhythm dysfunction in those conditions. **Mechanism — pulmonary effects (the aviptadil application context)**: VIP receptors are expressed on alveolar epithelium, vascular smooth muscle, and immune cells in the lung. Aviptadil — synthetic VIP — was investigated as IV and inhaled formulations for acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), particularly during the COVID-19 pandemic. The mechanistic rationale combined bronchodilation, anti-inflammatory effects, and pulmonary surfactant support. Phase III clinical trials in COVID-19 ARDS (NeuroRx / Relief Therapeutics) failed to meet primary endpoints; aviptadil is not FDA-approved as of catalog last update. The clinical trial failure does not negate VIP's mechanism but reflects the narrow application context — VIP at appropriate doses for appropriate indications has substantially different evidence than ARDS-specific intervention. **Pharmaceutical status**: VIP is NOT FDA-approved as a pharmaceutical drug for general use as of catalog last update. Aviptadil (Zyesami) was investigated for COVID-19 ARDS with Phase III completion but no FDA approval. Intracavernosal VIP combined with phentolamine (Invicorp) has approval in some non-US markets for erectile dysfunction. Compounded preparations available via integrative medicine compounding pharmacies for off-label use, primarily intranasal formulations following the Shoemaker CIRS protocol. **Pharmacokinetics**: very short plasma half-life (~2 minutes) — among the shortest plasma half-lives of any therapeutic peptide; intranasal route provides direct CNS access bypassing some BBB and hepatic first-pass metabolism limitations.",
