    sourcingNotes:
      "**Not FDA-approved** for general use. Available as compounded preparation via integrative medicine compounding pharmacies (Hopkinton Drug, ApothéCure, Tailor Made Compounding, others) with prescription. Shoemaker CIRS protocol is the principal clinical context — practitioners with CIRS / mold illness expertise (Surviving Mold practitioner network, related integrative medicine networks) typically prescribe and monitor. Aviptadil (Zyesami) is the synthetic VIP analog investigated by NeuroRx / Relief Therapeutics for COVID-19 ARDS; Phase III trials did not meet primary endpoints; not FDA-approved as of catalog last update. Quality varies substantially across compounding pharmacy sources; established pharmacies with track record in intranasal peptide compounding preferred.",
    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Shoemaker CIRS Protocol Workhorse\n\nVIP's principal modern clinical context is the **Shoemaker CIRS (Chronic Inflammatory Response Syndrome) protocol** for chronic biotoxin illness recovery. CIRS is a clinical framework developed by Ritchie Shoemaker MD describing chronic illness from biotoxin exposure (mold mycotoxins, Lyme-related toxins, certain seafood toxins, some bacterial toxins).\n\nThe Shoemaker protocol is a structured 12-step sequence:\n1. Removal from biotoxin exposure (mold remediation)\n2. Cholestyramine (CSM) or Welchol for biotoxin clearance\n3. Eradicate biofilm-forming bacteria (MARCoNS testing and treatment)\n4. Correct anti-gliadin antibodies (gluten avoidance)\n5. Correct androgens\n6. Correct ADH/osmolality\n7. Correct MMP-9 (matrix metalloproteinase 9)\n8. Correct VEGF\n9. Correct C3a\n10. Correct C4a\n11. Correct TGF-β1\n12. **Correct VIP — intranasal VIP** (the late-stage step)\n\nVIP intranasal is the final step in the protocol — used after biotoxin clearance and after most other inflammatory biomarkers have normalized. VIP normalizes T-regulatory cell function, completes HPA axis recovery, and supports the final restoration of immune regulation in CIRS recovery.\n\n**Critical practice point:** VIP use without prior biotoxin clearance and ongoing exposure remediation is contrary to Shoemaker protocol design and is not expected to produce sustained benefit. Users approaching VIP outside the protocol structure should coordinate with knowledgeable CIRS-literate practitioner.\n\n## Aviptadil — The COVID-19 ARDS Investigation\n\nAviptadil (Zyesami) is synthetic VIP investigated by NeuroRx / Relief Therapeutics for acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), particularly during the COVID-19 pandemic. The clinical trial program included Phase II and Phase III trials in COVID-19 ARDS with both IV and inhaled formulations.\n\n**Phase III trials did not meet primary endpoints.** Aviptadil is not FDA-approved as of catalog last update. The clinical trial failure does not negate VIP mechanism — VIP biology is well-established — but reflects the narrow application context: COVID-19 ARDS specifically did not respond to VIP intervention in the studied protocols. Users encountering aviptadil-specific clinical claims should be aware of this trial outcome.\n\nThe aviptadil program demonstrated that synthetic VIP can be manufactured at clinical scale and administered via multiple routes; the negative ARDS trials do not preclude future investigation in different indications or protocols.\n\n## Intranasal Route — Why It's Preferred\n\nIntranasal administration is the preferred VIP route in the Shoemaker CIRS protocol and most community use contexts:\n- **Direct CNS access** — partially bypasses BBB; relevant for CNS-mediated effects\n- **Lower systemic exposure** — reduces hypotension risk vs SubQ\n- **Practical self-administration** — nasal spray vs injection\n- **Established in published Shoemaker protocol literature**\n\nSubQ VIP is used in some research contexts but is less common in modern community use.\n\n## Hypotension Reality\n\nVIP's vasodilation effect produces dose-dependent hypotension. The intranasal route at standard CIRS protocol doses (50mcg QID) typically produces mild and well-tolerated effects, but:\n- Users with low baseline BP may experience symptomatic hypotension\n- Concurrent antihypertensives, PDE5 inhibitors, nitrates, alpha-blockers amplify effect\n- Initial titration dose (25mcg × 2 daily) helps assess tolerance\n- BP monitoring during titration is prudent\n\n## Synergies\n**BPC-157 and TB-500** — healing peptides; commonly combined with VIP for chronic inflammatory state recovery. **Thymosin Alpha-1** — immunomodulator; complementary mechanism for immune regulation. **Glutathione, NAD+** — foundational antioxidant / energy support. **Cholestyramine or Welchol** for ongoing biotoxin clearance support in CIRS contexts. **Methylation support** for metabolic recovery. **Adequate sleep, stress management** for HPA axis recovery alongside VIP.\n\n## Mold Illness / CIRS Context\n\nMold illness recovery via the Shoemaker protocol is the principal practical context for therapeutic VIP use. The CIRS framework is not universally accepted in conventional medicine — some Lyme literate / integrative medicine practitioners use modified protocols and some conventional immunologists question CIRS as a unified clinical entity. The framework has substantial real-world clinical use base in integrative medicine practice, with measurable biomarker outcomes (TGF-β1, MSH, MMP-9, C4a, VEGF, T-regulatory cells) supporting protocol effectiveness in many clinical contexts.\n\nUsers considering VIP for mold illness recovery should:\n- Address environmental exposure first (mold remediation, exposure avoidance)\n- Work with a CIRS-literate practitioner (Surviving Mold practitioner network, integrative medicine practitioners with CIRS training)\n- Complete prior protocol steps (biotoxin clearance, biomarker normalization) before VIP step\n- Approach VIP as the final protocol step rather than a standalone intervention\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-established via decades of neuropeptide research; receptor pharmacology, anti-inflammatory effects, and circadian rhythm roles all characterized. Clinical evidence base for Shoemaker CIRS protocol is largely Shoemaker's own published case series and protocol literature; independent replication is limited but growing within the CIRS-literate practitioner community. Aviptadil clinical trial program (Phase III ARDS) failed to meet primary endpoints — does not negate VIP mechanism but reflects narrow ARDS application context.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational VIP neuropeptide pharmacology well-characterized; receptor biology, anti-inflammatory effects, and circadian rhythm roles established; Shoemaker CIRS protocol literature published; aviptadil Phase III ARDS trials completed (failed primary endpoints). Anecdote: substantial Shoemaker CIRS protocol clinical use base; community familiarity with intranasal route and titration patterns; commonly stacked with healing peptides and CIRS protocol companion compounds. Decision frame: foundational neuropeptide with broadly anti-inflammatory and immunomodulatory effects; principal clinical context is Shoemaker CIRS protocol for chronic biotoxin illness recovery (late-stage protocol step after biotoxin clearance); intranasal route preferred over SubQ for community use; hypotension is the principal practical concern; aviptadil ARDS trial failure does not negate VIP mechanism but reflects narrow ARDS application context; the catalog does not provide specific protocol guidance per locked HRT/protocol rule.",
